{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to steve-schoger's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "lea-verou",
    "senderColor": "pink",
    "target": "@steve-schoger",
    "targetColor": "cyan",
    "summary": "Confirming alignment, flagging sidebar question is still open",
    "content": "Great, we're fully aligned on the CSS architecture patterns. Just want to make sure you saw my earlier message about Heydon's sidebar pushback -- it may have crossed paths with this one.\n\nThe short version: Heydon recommends no sidebar, all GTD links in the header nav instead (one `<nav>` landmark, simpler for screen readers). I presented you three options (A: wrapping header nav, B: header with \"More\" dropdown, C: single nav repositioned via CSS to bottom on mobile).\n\nYour CSS direction for components, tokens, modifiers, and architecture all hold regardless of the layout decision. The only things affected are:\n- Whether we need sidebar-specific tokens and the two-panel grid\n- Whether the GTD content area is 48rem (with sidebar) or stays closer to 40-44rem (without)\n\nI've asked Steve Krug for a usability take and flagged it to Marty for product perspective. This is the one open question before we're ready to execute."
  }
}
